- Annex A.14.2.5 Introduction

TES develops and maintains bespoke within various applications including Business Central (On Premise and SaaS), D365, Dynamics Nav, and .NET across its customer base.

Software development and maintenance is a critical component of the TES Development operation, and it is essential that it is professionally written and maintained.

Quality development offers many advantages:

&nbsp;

- Will contain fewer bugs, which will result in fewer future support calls.
- Functionality will run more efficiently with better performance.
- Future maintenance will be more manageable for the extended TES Development team.
- Increased productivity for the developer.

&nbsp;

Objectives of this document:

- Assist the development team in providing consistent, high quality, maintainable source code that can be shared in a team-based development environment.
- Code development and maintained to these software standards will reduce the cost of development.
- Ensure strict consideration is made to the way in which the Development team handle customer's data

It is essential that all development performed by TES Developers (and any other member of staff authorised to make code changes) is done using the standards stated in this document.

This applies to all projects, change requests and support cases; there are NO exceptions.

This document details both standards and guidelines. It is important to note the difference between standards and guidelines:

- Standards MUST be followed for all development produced by the TES development team and any other member of staff authorised to make code changes.
- Guidelines can be viewed as suggestions which can help developers produce high quality bespoke.

&nbsp;

It is important to note that standards and guidelines are likely to evolve over time.

TES will hold regular review sessions of these standards and Developers are encouraged to provide feedback to management.

Skills and Roles Matrix

All activities and tasks described in this document can only be performed by TES Employees that are authorised to do so.

The TES systems and roles matrix provides is continuously updated and must always be referred to.

- C/AL Coding Standards

Introduction

This section describes the coding Standards that must be adhered to for all Development that takes place within C/AL.

There are **no exceptions** to this rule - all code changes, however small must follows these standards.

Documentation and Version Control

Across the TES Customer base, an up-to date Development database is hosted on the Customer Server.

Within this database, TES install and maintain a Module known as IDYN Object Manager / OMA. This is the software used by TES for Source Control when developing in databases using C/AL.

Object Manager (OMA) - Changes to Objects

Before any changes are made to objects (this includes projects, changes requests, support calls), a project needs to be created in OMA. This provides the version no. that will be used to identify all changes made for this task.

This applies to the smallest of changes including adding a field to a page - there are **NO exceptions**.

![Graphical user interface, text, application, table

Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

The version no. provided by OMA (in the example above TES002) will be used by the developer to update the following:

- Version List of the object modified or created.
- Documentation Trigger of the object modified or created.
- In-code changes made as part of the bespoke.

Backup of OMA Data

Maintaining Object Manager (OMA) data is critical to the development operation. The developer should ensure that OMA project data is exported from the development database and then uploaded to the internal Sharepoint site.

Within Object Manager there is a function to facilitate the backup and restore of project data.

Project data will be exported as a dbk file. This file should be stored in the OMA Backup folder within the Customer's Technical folder on the internal TES Sharepoint site.

Object Numbering

New objects created along with new fields created in standard objects, should be numbered in the 50000 range. If bespoke is related to a specific IP module, a different number range might be allocated. Consideration should always be made to the objects available on the customer license.

Variable and Object Naming

With the move to Business Central and the AL Development environment, variable naming should be as close to the Microsoft standard as possible.

**Please view the following for a comprehensive description** **of these guidelines:**

[_https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dynamics-nav/naming-conventions_](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dynamics-nav/naming-conventions)

A selection of points from the above link:

- Ensure captions of all fields, include ENU and ENG.
- Two objects of the same type must not have the same name
- Each object should be named in a way that explains what it applies to. Good example is Customer Status. A bad example would be creating a table called Status as this is too generic.
- Table object must be named singular. The table name should also correspond to one record in a table.
- Naming pages depends on the page type. Singular form should be used for card pages and plural forms should be used for tabular pages. Example is Item Card, Item List.
- Field names:
- For new fields added to standard tables, this must be prefixed with TES
  - For example, if field "Job No." is added to a standard table, this should be added as "TES Job No.".
- Include "Date" when including a new date field. E.g., Posting Date
- Include % for a percentage field. E.g., Profit %
- Include Quantity or Qty. for a quantity field. E.g., Quantity Shipped
- Include No. for fields showing no. of entries. E.g., No. of Shipments
- Include Amount or Amt. for an amount field. E.g., Debit Amount
- Distinguish between costs, prices, and amounts E.g., Unit Cost, Unit Price, Unit Amount
- For flowfields, use Amounts instead of Amount E.g., Invoice Amounts
- For local currency include LCY E.g., Sales (LCY)
- If a field contains parentheses, put a space at the opening parentheses e.g., Sales (LCY)
- For Boolean fields, create field names as positive questions or statements E.g., Cost is adjusted
- If the primary key of a table is code, Code should be used as the name of a field that contains the data type code E.g., Code in the Location table
- In the situation where, numerical values are used as keys, but the data type is still code, the field should be named No. E.g., G/L Account table and field No.
- Variable names:
- Do not include spaces or other characters such as parentheses that would otherwise make quotation marks around a variable necessary.
  - Examples:
    - Customer
    - GenJnlBatch
- For currencies, replace the currency symbol with the currency unit code.
  - Example:
    - USD
    - TWD
- Name the "start" of variables with uppercase letters:
  - Example:
    - CustInvDiscAmountLCY
- If a variable with the same name already exists, either add a new variable to identify the variable or add the number 2 to the new variable name.
  - Example:
  - NewCustLedgEntry (which is recommended) or CustLedgEntry2
- Add Temp to the variable name for values stored temporarily
  - Example:
  - TempType
- If a variable is a record, page, report, xmlport, query or codeunit data type but the name also functions as a field name in other tables, we should add the appropriate suffix,
  - Example
  - SourceCodeRec - this is where the datatype is record and the data item is the source code table.
- Rec is added in this case as Source Code is also a field in various tables. Naming the variable SourceCode in this case would create confusion.
- Text Variables should always be created rather than hardcoding error, confirm and general messages within logic.

- C/AL Coding Guidelines

Spacing and Indentation

The use of space within code can enhance readability which is crucial for ongoing maintenance.

All code should be indented by 2-character spaces, achieved using the TAB key. As mentioned earlier in this document, all code

should be accompanied by the related TES Version No.

Common Code Structures

The following structures are typical examples within the Dynamics Nav development environment:

// Conditionally executing a set of commands based on the value of a logical expression.

IF Expression THEN BEGIN

Statement1;

END ELSE BEGIN

Statement2;

Statement3;

END;

- do not need BEGIN if the condition results in one statement IF a = b THEN

c := d;

//do not need ELSE part of the condition if there is no statement to execute.

END ELSE BEGIN

END;

// Executing a set of commands within a conditional loop.

IF Expression THEN BEGIN

REPEAT

Commands

UNTIL Expression

END ELSE BEGIN

Commands

END;

Error Trapping

The developer should trap error conditions in code and supply suitable messages written in good English to the end-user. This will assist end-users in resolving issues themselves without having to call support.

The developer should avoid using command TESTFIELD.

Whilst this function is useful it often does not provide the end-user with a meaningful message. This can be misleading to both the end-user and support personnel.

Setup Tables / Parameters

Data and settings should never be hardcoded in code. Best practice is to add new fields to an existing or new setup table which will allow the user to maintain / change these values in future.

Examples include:

- Setup fields for directory paths
- Number series for custom tables
- Default codes i.e., reason codes etc.
- Ensure new fields are always added to a new tab within the setup page.
- This should be named Bespoke unless advised otherwise by the customer or specification.

Multi-Language Captions

As a minimum, multi-language captions / option strings / text variable should have text for ENG and ENU.

General Coding Guidelines

Standard Code made redundant should never be deleted. The developer should always comment out code rather than deleting it.

Progress Indicator

Progress bars should always be included when routines are created. This is essential to provide the user of an indication of the running time of a routine.

Keys

Using the correct key is critical to performance. However, the developer should be aware that introducing too many keys can slow down performance of a database

Menu

Bespoke Setup pages should be added to a common place so that end-users, developers, and support personnel can easily access them.

Location should be:  
Administration, Application Setup, TES (New Group), Setup Pages.

The developer should always modify the PARTNER MenuSuite. Unless the bespoke is a new granule, bespoke setup pages should be added to the new folder, named "Bespoke", on the menu.

Option Fields

If a standard option field needs to be extended the developer should ensure that five commas are included before the new option value is added.

Example:  
Document Type:  
Before Modification:  
Quote,Order,Invoice,Credit Memo  
After Modification:  
Quote,Order,Invoice,Credit Memo,,,,,ProForma  
This approach ensures caters for any new options that Microsoft might add in future.

Changing field lengths of Standard Fields

The policy at TES is to NEVER increase or decrease the field length of standard fields.

Fields are used throughout the program, in relation to other tables and within code in functions which will expect the length originally provided by Microsoft.

Commenting out lines of code

Due to previous issues with powershell scripts, when commenting out code, we should do so as follows:

Do not use:

{

UserSetup.RESET;

UserSetup.SETFILTER("User ID", '%1', CodeUserID);

}

You should use:

//UserSetup.RESET;

//UserSetup.SETFILTER("User ID", '%1', CodeUserID);

This advice will be updated if Powershell is able to manage curly brackets.

4\. AL Coding Standards

TES Prefix

**The default prefix that should be used in all scenarios is:**

&nbsp;

**TES**

Further detail will be provided below on in which scenario's not to use this prefix, e.g., the 'name' property of a customer-specific extension.

Folder Structure Conventions

There should be two folders per extension, one called 'App' which will include all files related to the extension and another one called 'Test' which will include all files related to the extensions testing extension.

Both two folders will include the following:

- app.json
- AL object files
- Images
- Any metadata / user specific files i.e.
  - .vscode\\launch.json
  - .alpackages\\dependencies

Within both folders, a subfolder should be created called 'src' and in this folder subfolders should be created for each type of object where the AL object files (.al) are stored.

| --- | --- | --- |
| Table | TES NFP Setup | NFPSetup.Table.al |
| Table Extension | TES Purchase Header | PurchaseHeader.TableExt.al |
| Page | TES NFP Setup | NFPSetup.Page.al |
| Page Extension | TES Purchase Order | PurchaseOrder.PageExt.al |

Field Naming Convention

Formatting within AL Code

TES follow the following Microsoft guidelines:

e.g., OpenSalesQuote

- Use four spaces for indentation  
- Curly brackets should be placed on a new line

Variable naming

Variables should be named in the following way:

- PascalCase
- Use the Temp Prefix if they are temporary variables.
- Include the object name in the name (for objects).

Furthermore:

- Field and variable names should not include wildcard symbols, such as % and &. This might break features such as export using Excel or Rapid Start.
- Name fields using aA-zZ and 0-9 and use Caption and xliff files to display the field appropriately.
- Using English as the language for naming improves the ability to troubleshoot issues that may arise.

Method Declaration

To declare a method, follow these guidelines:

- Include one space after a semicolon when declaring multiple arguments.
- Semicolons can be used at the end of the signature / method header. If you use a snipped, the semicolons are not automatically added.
- Methods are named as variables using Pascal Case.
- There must be a blank line between method declarations. If you format your code using the AL Formatter tool, the auto-formatter sets the blank line between procedures.

&nbsp;

Example

local procedure MyProcedure(Customer: Record Customer; Int: Integer)

begin

end;

&nbsp;

// space local procedure MyProcedure2(Customer: Record Customer; Int: Integer)

begin

end;

Calling Methods

When calling a method, include one space after each command if you are passing multiple parameters.

Parentheses must be specified when you are making a method call or system call such as: Init(), Modify(), Insert() etc.  

e.g:

OpenCustomer('C0001');

OpenCustomer('C0001', Customer);

&nbsp;

Type definition (colon)

When declaring a variable or a parameter, the name of that variable or parameter must be immediately followed by a colon, then a single space, and then the type of the variable/parameter as illustrated in the example below.

Example

var

Number: Integer;

local procedure MyProcedure(a: Integer; b: Integer): Integer

Line length  

In general, there is no restriction concerning line length, but lengthy lines can make the code unreadable. We recommend that you keep your code easily scannable and readable.  

Global and Local Variables & Procedures

It is best practice to keep variables and procedures local unless they have a direct intention of being used from external objects or apps.

Versioning

For all extensions produced by TES the app.json file should contain the version of the app based on the following:

An always increasing set of four integers, separated by a dot, i.e., X.X.X.X. Upon increasing one of the integers, each integer to its right can be reset to zero.

The format of each integer in the version must be as follows:

**Non-IP Extensions**

| X   | X   | X   | X   |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| BC Major Release<br><br>e.g., 23 | TES (Publisher) Release - starting at 0 | Patch Version - starting at 0 | Release date in yyyyMMdd<br><br>i.e., 20210329 for 29<sup>th</sup> March 2021 |

e.g 23.0.12345.0

**IP Extensions**

| X   | X   | X   | X   |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| BC Major Release<br><br>e.g., 23 | TES (Publisher) Release - starting at 0 | Build version of Azure Pipeline | Always 0 |

e.g 23.0.0.20240126

**Non-IP Extensions**

Each release to a production environment no matter how small the change must increase at least the Patch Version and update the Release Date to today's date. (Change Requests changing existing features (if the change to the existing feature is extensive enough this may be considered a new feature and require the TES Release updating as below)).

For changes such as the release of a new feature(s) the TES Release must be increased, the Patch Version reset to 0 and the Release Date set to today's date. (Project & Change Request new features).

Finally for a new release of BC e.g., 18, the BC Major Release must be increased according to the number of the BC major release, TES Release reset to 1, Patch version reset to 0 and the Release Date set to today's date.

e.g.

- 17.1.0.20210329 - for initial release on 29/03/2021
- 17.1.1.20210401 - patch released on 01/04/2021
- 17.1.2.20210416 - patch released on 16/04/2021
- 17.2.0.20210503 - major TES release for this version of BC on 03/05/2021
- 18.1.0.20210401 - Microsoft major BC release of version 18 on 01/04/2021

5\. Source Control

Projects

- TES IP

A TES IP project exists in the 'TES365' Organisation of the Azure DevOps site. There is a repository for each TES IP Product.

- Customer Specific Extensions

A project will exist per customer in the 'TES365' organisation within the TES Azure DevOps platform. Each of these projects will contain a repository for each customer specific extension, i.e., there is a 'Total Enterprise Solutions' project containing extensions for our internal Business Central system.

- Repositories

A repository will exist per extension, whether that be a module of NFP or a customer specific extension. The repository name should specify the system and extension name, such as 'BC - DocumentApprovals' or 'BC- GeneralModifications'.

- Branches
- main

All repositories have one main branch, it will contain the latest signed-off version of the extension that can be deployed to a Production environment. No other branches should be used when deploying to a production environment, except in the case of a new release or hotfix. Once a release or hotfix branch has been deployed, this must be pulled into the main branch.

Commits may only be pulled into the main branch via a pull request from either the release or hotfix branches, where unit, functional and automated testing, alongside any test scripts are required to have been completed with 100% success.

**Naming Convention**: master or main

- Release

All repositories will have a release branch created based on the master branch, which will then run continuously alongside the master/main branch. The release branch will contain all development that will be a part of this release once that development is ready to be tested and then signed off for release to a production environment.

Commits may only be pulled into the release branch via a pull request from either the development or hotfix branches, where unit and automated testing alongside any test scripts are required to have been completed with 100% success.

**Naming Convention**: release/CHG000000 / release/v23.0.1.0

Feature / Project / Change Request/ Bugs

A branch must be created for each new feature, project or change request to an extension.

Commits may be pushed into a feature branch and no testing needs to be completed.

**Naming Convention**: users/john-doe/CHG00300 **or** users/john-doe/#15533_AppDimSelection

Forks

Currently forks are not to be used as part of the development process.

Pull Requests

When moving code from one branch to another, a pull request must be used. As a part of completing a pull request (when you press "Complete"), you will be asked to select a "Merge Type," currently you should select "Squash commit."

Commits

Commits MUST end with the work item ID you are working on, in the format:

# {work-item-id}, e.g., #420

Following the above ID must be a more detailed explanatory text. Explain the problem that this commit is solving. Focus on why you are making this change as opposed to how (the code explains that). Are there side effects or other unintuitive consequences of this change? Here is the place to explain them.

Further paragraphs come after blank lines.

\- Bullet points are okay, too

\- Typically, a hyphen is used for the bullet, preceded

by a single space, with blank lines in between.

Code Reviews

Code reviews are an essential part of TES Quality Assurance. Software code reviews for Microsoft Dynamics 365 Business Central and Dynamics 365 are a crucial element of ensuring quality, security and maintainability of all Software developed by TES for its Customers.  

The key objectives of the TES Code Review process are:

- Ensure adherence to TES Development Guidelines and Coding Standards and thus ensuring delivery of a

quality solution to the customer.

- Enhancing team collaboration
- Promoting knowledge sharing among team members
- Identify bugs at an early stage.

### Roles and Responsibilities

TES Code Reviews can be conducted by one of several technical resources employed by Total Enterprise Solutions.  

Conducting a code review assumes significant responsibility and for this reason, colleagues authorised to conduct code reviews are recorded within the TES System and Roles Matrix.  

Conducting a code review requires a systematic and thorough approach to ensure code quality, maintainability, and adherence to TES Development and Coding Standards.  

### Scope of when Code Reviews are required

All pull requests for Release and Main / Default branches must go through the Code Review process that is described in the official Code Review Procedure. This procedure can be located via the official TES Master Documentation spreadsheet in the Development team on Microsoft teams.

6\. Database Standards

Introduction

TES currently support Dynamics Nav / Business Central databases ranging from versions 5.1 through to the latest Business Central offering via SaaS.

Database creation across all versions is an important part of the Development operation and the following naming conventions should be always followed.

On-Prem Database Installation and Naming

TES install Dynamics Nav and Business Central On-Premises at the request of our Customers. Part of the installation will involve the installation of an out-of-the-box Dynamics Nav / Business Central SQL Database.

The number of databases created and how they are named must always follow the same standards as described in this section.

It is important to note that the data contained within these databases is Demo data supplied by Data i.e., no real-life data exists at this point.

Hosted on Customer Server - New Installations:

TES will deploy two databases during installation, both will be based on the out-of-the-box SQL Demo database provided by Microsoft.

Test / UAT databases are NOT deployed at this point in the project and are only created once the Customer is Live.

It is important to note that the Customer does reserve the right to insist on their own Database Naming Standards. However, TES do strongly recommend the conventions described below.

- - Development Database.

This should be named: CUSTOMER_DEV

This database is fully managed and controlled by TES. This is the database that will have Object Manager installed for source control and will be used for all Development activities.

- - Pre-Production / Pre-Live Database.

This should be named: CUSTOMER_LIVE

This database will:

- - - Be used by the Customer to configure Setup data and Configuration in preparation for going live.
      - Will contain real-life data once the project commences.
      - This database will also be used by the customer to conduct testing including for any bespoke that is delivered during the in-flight project lifecycle.
      - This is the database that will be used by the customer when the go live.

Hosted on 1-ClickFactory - New Installations

If the On-Premises database is hosted on Azure but within the 1-Click Factory Platform, neither TES nor the Customer can control what Database Name is allocated. 1-ClickFactory dictates database naming conventions.

Development Database - UidOffset ID

All Development Databases should have the database property Start ID (UidOffset) set to 1850000000. This is set from within the development environment, click on Database, click on Alter, and go to the Advanced Tab.

Following this change all new functions, variables, and data items that are added by TES will have the ID set to 1850000000. This is important as might help us avoid conflicts when merging TES bespoke with another partner's bespoke later i.e., if we do not change this value, we will be assigned the default value as any other Dynamics Nav partner will be. If we merge our bespoke into the bespoke of another Dynamics NAV partner, we could have issues with the same ID being used. Changing this value should help us avoid this issue.

Development Database - Recovery Mode

When creating a development database, we should remember to set the recovery mode to **Simple** during the restore process. This helps avoid transaction logs which can take up un-necessary space for a development database.

**Initial Installation - Pre-Go Live**

Business Central SaaS Database Installation and Naming

TES install and configure Business Central SaaS environments at the request of its customers. This installation will involve the installation of an out-of-the-box Business Central SaaS data set that will be hosted on Microsoft's Azure Servers in the cloud. The number of environments/databases created and how they are named must always follow the same standards as described in this section. It is important to note that the data contained within these databases is Demo data supplied by Data i.e., no real-life data exists at this point.

SaaS Installations

TES will create TWO environments/databases during installation, and both will contain Demo data provided by Microsoft. Test / UAT database/environments are NOT created at this point in the project and are only created once the Customer is Live.

It is important to note that the data is stored within the Cloud and on Microsoft Azure databases. For this reason, TES and the Customer do not have any access to the actual SQL database and therefore do not have access to the naming of the SQL Server or Database.

Environment Naming Standards:

Although TES cannot determine the database name, TES can control the name of the environments that are created during installation. The following standards must be adhered to:

- Development Database.

This will be a Sandbox environment and should be called:

**Development**

This will be a development environment that is controlled and managed by TES and will be used for all Development activities.

- Pre-Production / Pre-Live Database

This will be a Production Environment that will be called:

**Production**

- Be used for testing and pre-live setup and config.
- This database will become the Customer's Live database once we go-live.
- Contain real-life data once the project commences.
- This database will also be used by the Customer to conduct testing including for any bespoke that is delivered during the in-flight project lifecycle.

Example:

**Post Go-Live**

Once the customer is live an additional environment **UAT** must be created as a copy of Production.

- Be used for Customer testing before changes are deployed to production.

**New projects for Live Customers**

If a second project (Phase 2) development begins once a customer has gone live additional environments must be created.

- UAT Phase 2
  - Customers' environment for testing the new project changes.
- Development Phase 2

**Note:** additional environments may need to be purchased.

Trial Environments

If a customer requests an environment to host a trial of Total Enterprise Solutions IP a separate sandbox environment **TESIP_Trial** must be created unless the customer requests to use an existing Development or UAT sandbox.

If a customer requests a trial of another third-party extension the environment must at a minimum include Trial.

In all trial scenarios, the environment must be of type Sandbox.

7\. Information Security

Rules

The following rules must always be adhered to when handling customer's data. **There are NO exceptions to the following rules:**

- When a Bespoke change is requested by the Customer, it is TES policy for all customers (existing and new) to provide TES with an environment on the Customers own network for TES to make the required changed.
- Customer Databases are never to be stored on the TES network for data protection reasons.
- If TES are commissioned to create a Test Database using a backup from a Production Database, this must always be restored within the Customer's own network and never copied / restored to the TES Network, TES Employee's own laptops or external storage devices.
- When restoring a production backup or any backup containing customer data, existing permissions to that data must be maintained.
- If for technical reasons, existing permissions cannot be maintained, and login / permission information needs to be removed from the new Test Database, TES should ensure that the Customer provides TES with login information for at least one approved Super User.
- The approved Super User employed by the customer will then be responsible for managing User access as per their own procedures.
- When restoring a production backup or any backup containing customer data, TES should **NEVER** do the following:
- Leave the database without any logins which would mean the database is not secured.
- Assign non-approved users with SUPER user permissions.
- Passwords should never be documented in emails, written down or included in documentation (including release notes and specifications).
- If a customer's database must be sent to Microsoft for investigation of an issue, strict procedures must be adhered to before this can take place.
- Non-disclosure agreements are required. If the Developer needs to propose this course of action, he or she should progress this via the TES Support Department.

Customer Data Management

Process

All TES employees must adhere to the **"TES Data Management Procedure"** that is hosted in the TES Hi-Comply portal. This procedure covers both the handling and storage of Customer data.

Although the following provides an overview of the responsibilities for all TES Staff, employees must login to Hi-Comply and refer to the latest version of the "TES Data Management Procedure".

Data Handling

Data must be handled in accordance with its information classification, detailed in the information classification policy (ISMS-02-010).

- Customer Data Received

If any customer system data is received on any TES Infrastructure, it must be immediately and permanently deleted.

This rule also applies to emails; the incoming file must be deleted from the inbox and deleted items folder.

Examples of customer system data are as follows:

 Customer CRM system data - E.g., Contacts and accounts

 Customer BC/NAV system data - E.g., G/L Entries, Customers, Vendors, banks

 Any Customer data, including tests data that has not been anonymised

Data Storage

All Customer collateral including the latest version of all files must be stored within the main TES Sharepoint Site. This includes Commercial, Project and Technical collateral.

Customer files (any version) must never be stored on individual team sites, employees OneDrive accounts, emails or on local devices.

Documents and files with the appropriate information classification can be copied to an Individual Team Sites (e.g., used for a customer project) for the purposes of collaboration; however, the original copy / latest version of the document must remain stored in the primary TES SharePoint site.

Updating Documentation

Updates to all documents, including in-progress updates, must take place via a version that is stored on the primary TES Sharepoint site.

Sending Documentation to Customers

All documents sent to Customers (via any method of transfer) must always be taken from the Primary SharePoint site and never from individual teams' sites, employees OneDrive accounts, emails, or local devices.

Software Testing

TES Unit and Functional testing must only be performed with Dummy / demo / sample data. TES must not use and store Live customer data for any testing.

When requesting data from the customer for testing bespoke, TES must make it clear that Demo data is required.

If TES receive customer data from a customer via any method, the TES employee must follow the process described in the "TES Data Management Procedure".

Bespoke Documentation

Customer data must never be included in any documentation created by TES.

This includes screen shots of Customer data within Release notes and user guides.

If the documentation relates to a change to resolve an incident in a live environment and a screen shot is required, all customer data should be anonymised.

Source Control / File Sharing:

Bespoke / Files should only ever be stored in one of the following secure places - no exceptions:

 TES Network (Sharepoint)

 TES Azure Dev Ops Repository

 Customer's own Server in a location agreed by the Customer.

**Bespoke / Files should never be stored in a public repository.**

8\. Development Process Standards

Types of Development activity

TES Developers will be requested to develop software for the following services:

- TES IP
  - This is software TES build that can be used by more than one Customer.
- Customer Projects
  - This is software TES Builds that is customised for a specific Customer Project.
- Managed Services
  - Providing fixes for bugs
  - Developing small customisations for a customer that is live

Specification Rules

Rules

Development will only commence once the following is in place:

- TES IP

TES IP must always have a work item detailing the development activity required. New modules or large enhancements must always have a specification that has been approved by the TES Development Manager.

All TES IP specifications are created on the TES Azure Dev Ops Platform. Work must not proceed without a work item being created within the TES IP Project on Azure Dev Ops. This includes bugs fixes reported via the Service Now portal.

- Customer Project Work

Development work relating to a Customer Project must take place against a Specification signed by the Customer.

- Managed Services

Bug and minor changes are managed by the TES Managed Services Manager via the Service Now portal.

Risk Assessment

Risk Assessments must take place and be evidenced during the Specification stage for all Development Activity.

Consideration must be given to the impact each code change could have on Information Security.

Considerations for the impact on Information Security must take place continuously during the lifecycle of all Development activity including coding and Testing.

Scheduling, Diary Entries, Timesheets

TES IP, Customer Project Activity and Managed Services Change Requests

- Scheduling

TES IP and Customer Project delivery activity must always be scheduled in the Developer's Outlook diary by TES Scheduling team.

The Developer must not:

- Complete any Project or TES IP development tasks without this first being scheduled in their diary by Scheduling.
- Complete any Project or TES IP development tasks that are scheduled outside of our Scheduling team:

For example,

- - The Developer must not proceed with a development task if this is scheduled directly by a Project Manager without scheduling being included on the invite.
    - The Developer must not proceed with a development task if this is scheduled by any other employee at TES without scheduling being included on the invite.
- Diary Entry

It is the Developer's responsibility to ensure all time worked at TES is accounted for.

To facilitate this, the Developer must ensure each diary entry conforms to the following structure:

- Subject includes:
  - Full name of the customer, not abbreviated
  - Full description of the project being worked on
  - Confirmation of the task i.e. Development, Installation, Unit Testing, Documentation, Deployment
- Body includes:
  - Link to the specification / task being worked on

The Developer must retrospectively update the diary entry to indicate if the work did proceed as planned. For example, if the Developer was scheduled on remediation but no code changes were made, the developer should go back to the diary entry and make a note for future reference.

- Timesheets

It is the Developer's responsibility to ensure all time worked at TES is accounted for.

Managed Services Cases

- Scheduling

Managed Services are responsible for scheduling time for a Developer to work on incidents within Managed Services.

- Diary Entry

It is the Developer's responsibility to ensure all time worked at TES is accounted for.

To facilitate this, the Developer must ensure each diary entry conforms to the following structure:

- Subject includes:
  - Reference to working on Managed Service Incidents / Cases
- Body includes:
  - List of incidents / cases worked on

The Developer must retrospectively update the diary entry to indicate if the work did proceed as planned. For example, if two of five incidents were not worked on, the developer should go back into the diary entry (or ensure Managed Services team do this) and make a note for future reference.

Source Control

Please refer to the Source Control section within this document.

Coding and Development

Coding and Development must adhere to the standards and guidelines described in this document.

Quality Assurance

Please refer to the Quality Assurance section within this document.

Documentation

Customer facing release notes need to be created for all Development tasks executed by the Developer at TES, there are no exceptions.

This includes:

- Change Requests relating to cases and standard changes
- Projects
- TES IP
- Tenant Installations including additional new environments and the installation of apps
- POC Activity

Release notes must be created to a professional standard. Refer to the Documentation Standards section of this document.

Testing

Testing is a critical element of development.

TES Testing Cycle

The following is an overview only, all Developers and Testers must refer to the official "TES Testing Procedure" for the latest standards and guidelines that relate to unit and functional testing.

For all Types of Development (listed above), the following Testing takes place before any change is released to a customer for their testing:

- Developer Unit Testing
  - In addition to executing Tests designed by the Solution Architect, the Developer will design and execute their own Unit Tests to support the functionality being developed.
  - All testing must be completed on the TES Azure Dev Ops platform.
  - All testing executed must be evidenced with screen shots or recording.

- Functional Testing
  - Once the Developer has completed Development of a Development Activity, internal TES Functional Testing will be scheduled on a member of the TES Testing team. TES employ a dedicated Tester and use Application Consultants for Functional Testing.
  - All testing must be completed on the TES Azure Dev Ops platform.
  - All testing executed must be evidenced with screen shots or recording.
  - TES Functional testing must take place in the Customer's UAT environment unless authorised differently in writing from the Project / Managed Service Manager.

Important

Unit and Functional Testing can only be performed by TES Employees that are authorised to do so.

The TES systems and roles matrix provides is continuously updated and must always be referred to.

TES Staff authorised to execute Unit and Functional Testing must refer to the official "TES Functional Testing" documentation this is available within the TES Certified platform.

Customer User Acceptance Testing (UAT)

For all Types of Development, the Customer must perform their own testing in a copy of Production (UAT environment) and sign this off in writing before TES will deploy the change to a Production Environment.

Deployment

Deploying bespoke for TES Functional Testing and Customer UAT

Authorisation

Important

Deployment to UAT can only be performed by TES Employees that are authorised to do so.

The TES systems and roles matrix provides is continuously updated and must always be referred to.

The Developer must obtain permission in writing from the Project Manager or Managed Services Manager before any deployment to UAT takes place.

Environment

All Functional testing executed by TES must be performed in the Customer's UAT environment.

The TES Development environment must not be used for Functional testing unless authorised in writing by the Managed Services

or Dev Ops Manager.

TES Unit, Functional testing must never take place directly in a Customer's Production environment.

Process

- The Developer must always deploy extensions through the application itself, from the Extension Management page.
- The Developer must never deploy extensions to a Customer's UAT environment via VS Code.

Deploying directly through VS Code can result in extensions being automatically un-installed by Microsoft during monthly updates.

- Release notes must be completed ahead of any deployment to UAT.
- If a new environment is required for TES Functional Testing or Customer UAT, authorisation is required in writing from both the TES Project / Managed Services Manager and Customer.

This is essential for two key reasons 1. The UAT environment is owned by the Customer 2. The creation of a new environment could result in the customer in the short, medium, or long-term having to pay for additional capacity.

- Job queues must never be switched on in a UAT environment without written permission from both the Project / Managed Services at TES and the Customer.

Deploying bespoke to Production Environment

Authorisation

Important

Deployment to UAT can only be performed by TES Employees that are authorised to do so.

The TES systems and roles matrix provides is continuously updated and must always be referred to.

The Developer must obtain permission in writing from both the TES Project Manager or Managed Services Manager and the Customer before any deployment to Production takes place.

Process

Deployment for all changes must be conducted using the latest "Bespoke Deployment Guidelines Template".

The "Bespoke Deployment / Guidelines Template" contains all the rules that must be strictly adhered to when deploying to Customer Production environments.

Each deployment to Production, however small and related to any purpose, must be both executed and documented using the "Bespoke Deployment Guidelines Template" and stored in the relevant Customer folder within the primary TES Sharepoint site.

Here are some of the key areas that form part of the TES Deployment process:

- TES have executed and passed both Unit and Functional Testing.

Unit and Functional Testing must be evidenced on the TES Azure Dev Ops platform.

- The customer has in writing confirmed successfully executing and passing their own User Acceptance Testing (UAT).
- Authorisation for the deployment has been granted in writing by both the TES Project / Managed Services Manager and the Customer themselves.
- Some customers require a CAB (change approval board) form to be populated before any changes can be deployed into their live database.
- As described in the "Bespoke Deployment Guidelines Template", the TES Developer should follow the following strict rules before deploying changes into a customer's live or a Customer's UAT database:
- Agree a date and time with the customer for the import to take place and provide an estimation to the customer of likely down time. Advise if users should be logged out of the system during deployment and if any service restarts are required.
- Backup and Rollback plans
- Communicate to both the TES Project / Managed Services Manager and the Customer that the deployment is completed. Update Internal Systems.

C/AL Code Archiving Policy on Customer Server

Note: This policy only applies to c/al based development taking place on a customer server and excludes AL Extension based solution development.

Before making any code changes, the developer should ensure that the following folder structure is in place on the Customer server:

\\TES\\Changes

\\TES\\Incidents

\\TES\\Projects

\\TES\\License

\\TES\\Temp

Examples of subfolders:

\\TES\\Changes\\CHGXXXXXXX\\Backup

\\TES\\Changes\\CHGXXXXXXX\\Deployment

\\TES\\Incidents\\INCXXXXXXX\\Backup

\\TES\\Incidents\\INCXXXXXXX\\Deployment

IMPORTANT: The TES development license file (.flf) should NEVER be left on a customer server.

The TES license should be deleted / removed from the customer server once we have finished working on the server.

Code Archiving Policy - TES Sharepoint Site

**This applies to all changes including C/AL and Extensions**.

All bespoke (C/AL and Extensions) must be uploaded to the relevant folder on Sharepoint - along with a strict naming convention:

| Folder on Sharepoint | Subfolder on Sharepoint | Subfolder on Sharepoint | C/AL |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| TES General \\ Customers \\ CUSTOMER001\\ | 06 Incidents | Backup<br><br>Deployment | Backup(s) from Live database before deployment<br><br>INCXXXXXXX V1.fob |
| TES General \\ Customers \\ CUSTOMER001\\ | 03 Change Requests | Backup<br><br>Deployment | Backup(s) from Live database before deployment<br><br>CHGXXXXXXX V1.fob |
| TES General \\ Customers \\ CUSTOMER001\\ | 02 Projects | Backup<br><br>Deployment | Backup(s) from Live database before deployment<br><br>PROJECTNAME V1.fob |

IMPORTANT: As shown above, for Extensions, the folder name should be made up as:

- INCIDENT / CHANGE / Project No.
- Name of the Extension
- Version of the Extension

Contents of the extension should be stored within the folder.

C/AL Fob File naming convention

Fob files should be named as follows:

CUSTOMERNAME CHGXXXXXXX V1

If following TES or Customer testing, further changes are required, another version of the fob file will be released:

CUSTOMERNAME CHGXXXXXXX V2

Release Notes naming convention

Release notes are named as follows:

CUSTOMERNAME CHGXXXXXXX Release Notes V1

If following TES or Customer testing, further changes are required, another version of the release notes will be created:

CUSTOMERNAME CHGXXXXXXX Release Notes V2

All versions of fob files and release notes should be uploaded to the relevant customer folder on the main TES sharepoint site.

Code changes that do not go Live

There are occasions when code changes are made and applied to both the Development and UAT databases but are no longer required to be imported into the Live / Production Database. This can be due to any of the following reasons:

- The customer no-longer wants the change.
- If related to a support call or change request, the customer did not test on time and / or failed to respond to TES and the call is then closed by TES.

**In this situation we need to ensure that the code changes are completely reversed from the UAT and Dev databases (a backup should be taken first and placed on the TES Sharepoint site).**

Managing Third-party dependencies

- Overview

Bespoke solutions supplied to Customers by TES can include a dependency on one or more third-party products.

A third-party product must only be used in a TES Solution if it is specified within the signed specification.

- Register of third-party dependencies

All third-party dependencies must be added to the official register which is stored within the TES Sharepoint site. This can be found via the TES Technical Documentation master spreadsheet via the General channel within the Development team on Microsoft Teams.

- Signing up to Third Party websites

For ISMS purposes, members of the TES Technical team must continue to sign up to third-party product websites using individual email addresses.

- Alerting the business to changes

If the TES resource receives an update regarding a Third-party product dependency, they must forward the communication to <Technical@totalenterprisesolutions.co.uk>

- Monitoring and executing actions from changes

TES hold a recurring Third-party dependency review meeting that takes place once per quarter. This includes all members of the Design team, the TES IP Product Manager and Development Manager.

Any actions that arise from the meeting are added as tasks to the D365/BC channels in Microsoft Teams.

9\. Documentation Standards

Introduction

All documentation created for both Internal use and for use by external parties including Customers must be of a consistent quality.

Documentation standards exists because documentation is often the most tangible way of representing the software that has been developed along with its related processes.

Standardised documents have a consistent appearance, structure and quality which will ensure they are understandable to the viewer.

Standards

All technical documentation created by the developer must adhere to the following rules:

- The document must be created using an official TES Template that can be found within the Technical Master spreadsheet that resides on the Development Teams site.

This spreadsheet includes links to all technical templates that are stored on the main TES Sharepoint site.

- All Templates must use the TES Branding that was introduced in 2021.
- The contents page, headings and page numbers must always be updated before releasing the document.
- The contents page must only contain headings and not body text.
- A consistent font and font size must be used throughout the document. There must not be any inconsistency with the font used for sections and the body within the same document.
- There must not be any inconsistency with the font size used for Headings, Subheadings and text that forms the body.

i.e., all Headings should have the same font size, all Sub-Headings should have the same font size, all body text throughout the document should have the same font size.

- The Spell check must always be run, and any issues addressed before releasing the document.
- The Grammar check must always be run, and any issues addressed before releasing the document.
- Where a template instructs the developer to remove wording or a section, this must be done before making the document ready for distribution.
- All "Headings" (Major sections) must start on a new page. For example, this section (16 Documentation Standards) has been created on a new page rather than at the bottom of the previous page that relates to Section 15 (Government Technology Code of Practice).
- All "Sub-Headings" must be presented in a professional manner and must start on a new page if sufficient space does not exist on the current page.
- If sufficient space does not exist to place a table, start this on a new page.
- Screen shots:
  - Only include screen shots where necessary.
  - When including a screen shot, ensure this is always aligned in the centre.
  - Ensure screen shots look professional and only contained required information
  - Never include customer data on screen shots. Refer to Demo data only.
- Customer Data
  - Never include customer data in any documentation. Screen shots must always display demo data.

10\. Quality Assurance

Quality is one the key values that defines Total Enterprise Solutions. TES strive for the highest quality in every interaction that is made with its Customers. This includes all aspects of the operation ranging from our Commercial and Back-Office teams to delivering Software Services.

TES develops and maintains bespoke within various applications including Business Central (On Premise and SaaS), D365, Dynamics Nav, and .NET across its customer base. The standards and guidelines described in this document have the purpose of ensuring that TES deliver the highest quality software to its customers.

Role

TES commitment to Quality is demonstrated by a full-time role that exists in the business. TES employ a Development and Quality Manager who is responsible for ensuring that all Development activity adheres to the standards and guidelines described in this document.

Auditing and Compliance

The Development and Quality Manager at TES conducts monthly audits across all Development Activity, including Projects, Managed Services, and its own Product portfolio.

Issue identified are added to a compliance register and then managed through to a point where the risk has been mitigated.

In-Project Quality Assurance Checks / Peer Reviews

QA checks / Peer Reviews are a central part of the Software Development lifecycle at TES. Each Development Project is scoped to include dedicated Quality Assurance Checks that will take place between the original Solution Architect and the Developer who is creating the solution.

QA checks / Peer Reviews are conducted throughout the duration of a Software project to ensure that the solution being developed is in line with expectations set out in the specification and adheres to the standards and guidelines described in this document.

Issues identified during a QA Check are added as actions to the QA / Peer Review Log where they are then managed through to completion.

Reporting

Quality statistics that result from the Monthly audits are presented to the Senior Management Team at TES. Areas of concern are raised and discussed as are actions to mitigate risk.

Development Meeting

All Developer's across the business are required to attend the weekly Development Meeting. Auditing, Compliance, QA Checks, and Improvements to the operation are all topics that can be part of the agenda.

The weekly development meeting is essential in ensuring consistent adherence by all technical staff to TES Coding Standards and Development Process.

Continual Improvement

TES strive to continually improve the quality of the Development Operation and thus increasing the quality of software solutions delivered to our Customers. Auditing is central to this and provides a continual feedback loop of improvement.

TES also maintain a CSI (Continual Service Improvement) log which drives improvements in Service quality across all areas of the business.

Staff Engagement

Compliance to the TES Development Process, is one of the objectives that TES Project Developers work to on a quarterly basis. Compliance to the TES development process is a topic for discussion within individual 1-1 sessions.

Code Reviews

Code Reviews for all changes form part of the TES Development process. Please refer to the relevant section, early in this document.
